{
  "doc_id": "23929",
  "text": "Activation of ATM and ATR signaling results in activation of p53 with a concomitant growth arrest that would be detrimental for viral replication in dividing cells. However, several studies have shown that the ability of E6 to degrade and/or inactivate p53 is crucial for long-term genome maintenance [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Furthermore, inactivation of p53 or expression of a dominant negative p53 protein can complement genomes defective for E6 expression [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
